window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"objective>Physics>2002>1","subject":"Physics","year":"2002","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPTS OF MATTER : CONCEPTS OF MATTER","question":"One common characteristics of solid, liquid and gases is that","images":[],"options":{"A":"all the three have fixed volume","B":"their molecules have the same size","C":"their molecular are always in motion","D":"all the three have the same inter molecular forces"},"answer":"C","explanation":"One common characteristic of solids, liquids, and gases is that their molecules are always in motion. This is based on the kinetic theory of matter, which states that all matter is composed of particles (molecules, atoms, or ions) that are in constant motion.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2002>2","subject":"Physics","year":"2002","type":"Objective","topic":"FLUID AT REST : PRESSURE IN FLUIDS","question":"the forces between the molecules of a liquid in contact with that of a solid is","images":[],"options":{"A":"adhesive","B":"cohesive","C":"magnetic","D":"repulsive"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The forces between the molecules of a liquid in contact with that of a solid are adhesive forces. Adhesive forces refer to the attractive force between two unlike molecules. They are caused by forces of attraction between different substances, such as mechanical and electrostatic forces.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2002>3","subject":"Physics","year":"2002","type":"Objective","topic":"STRUCTURE OF THE NUCLEUS : COMPOSITION OF THE NUCLEUS","question":"The energy needed to separated the nucleons against the forces which hold them together is","images":[],"options":{"A":"nuclear energy","B":"mechanical energy","C":"ionisation energy","D":"binding energy"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The energy needed to separate the nucleons against the forces which hold them together is known as binding energy. Binding energy is the energy required to disassemble a whole system into separate parts. A bound system typically has a lower potential energy than its constituent parts; this is what keeps the system together. The difference in potential energy is known as the binding energy.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2002>4","subject":"Physics","year":"2002","type":"Objective","topic":"FLUID AT REST : PRESSURE IN FLUIDS","question":"A reservoir is filled with a liquid of density 2000kgm-3. calculate the depth at which the pressure in the liquid will be equal to 9100Nm-2.[g ^ 10ms-2].","images":[],"options":{"A":"0.262m","B":"0.455m","C":"0.664m","D":"0.8119m"},"answer":"B","explanation":"P = \u03c1gh  (\u03c1 = density, h = depth, g = 10m/s2)  9100 = 2000 \u00d7 10 \u00d7 h  h=910020,000=0.455m","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2002>5","subject":"Physics","year":"2002","type":"Objective","topic":"FLUID AT REST : VOLUME, DENSITY AND RELATIVE DENSITY","question":"solid weighs 45N and 15N respectively in air and water.Determine the relative density of the solid","images":[],"options":{"A":"0.33","B":"0.50","C":"1.50","D":"3.00"},"answer":"C","explanation":"R.D=weight in airupthrust  Weight in air = 45N  Weight in water = 15N  Upthrust = 45 - 15 = 30N  R.D = 45N/30N = 1.5","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2002>6","subject":"Physics","year":"2002","type":"Objective","topic":"POSITION, DISTANCE AND DISPLACEMENT : DISTINCTION BETWEEN DISTANCE AND DISPLACEMENT.","question":"A boy travels 8km eastward to a point B and ten 6km northward to another point c, determine the difference between the magnitude of displacement of the boy and distance travelled by him.","images":[],"options":{"A":"2.0km","B":"4.0km","C":"10.0km","D":"14.0km"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The difference in the displacement = length OC    OC2 = OB2 + BC2    \u21d2 82 + 62  \u21d2 = 64 + 36  OC2 = 100  squaring both sides  OC = 10km  total distance  = 14km  Difference between distance and displacement  = 14 - 10 km = 4km","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2002>7","subject":"Physics","year":"2002","type":"Objective","topic":"MOTION : SIMPLE IDEAS OF CIRCULAR MOTION","question":"The magnitude of the force required to make an object of mass, m move with speed, v in a circular path of radius. is given by the expression","images":[],"options":{"A":"mr/v","B":"mr2/v","C":"mv2/r","D":"mv/r2"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The force required to keep an object moving in a circular path is given by the centripetal force formula, which is F = mv^2 / r, where m is the mass of the object, v is the speed of the object and r is the radius of the circular path. Hence, the correct option is 3.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2002>8","subject":"Physics","year":"2002","type":"Objective","topic":"MOTION : TYPES OF MOTION","question":"A man was moving round a circular path continuously for 4 minutes and covered the following distance in the times stated below   Distance(in metres) 200 400 600 800Time (in minutes) 1 2 3 4. which of the following statement is correct about the motion of the man?","images":[],"options":{"A":"The man was moving with uniform speed but non-uniform velocity","B":"The speed was changing constantly","C":"The velocity was uniform","D":"it was an instance of motion is which both speed and velocity are the same"},"answer":"A","explanation":"V=2001=4002=6003=8004=200m/min  Uniform speed but direction keeps changing","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2002>9","subject":"Physics","year":"2002","type":"Objective","topic":"RECTILINEAR ACCELERATION : EQUATIONS OF MOTION WITH CONSTANT ACCELERATION","question":"A car take of from rest and cover a distance of 80m on a straight road in 10s. calculate the magnitude of its acceleration","images":[],"options":{"A":"1.25ms-2","B":"1.60ms-2","C":"4.00ms-2","D":"8.00ms-2"},"answer":"B","explanation":"U = 0 (starting from rest)  Using newton's third law of motion  s=ut+12at2  80=0\u00d7t+12a102  80=12a102  160 = 100a  a = 1.6m/s2","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2002>10","subject":"Physics","year":"2002","type":"Objective","topic":"RECTILINEAR ACCELERATION : MOTION UNDER GRAVITY","question":"An object is released from rest at a height of 25m. calculate the time it takes to fall to the ground [g = 10ms-2]","images":[],"options":{"A":"25.00s","B":"10.00s","C":"2.50s","D":"2.24s"},"answer":"D","explanation":"u = o (starting from rest)  s=ut+12at2  s=12at2(sinceu=0)  25=12x10xt2  t2=255  t2 = 5  t = 2.24s","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2002>11","subject":"Physics","year":"2002","type":"Objective","topic":"EQUILIBRIUM OF FORCES : CONDITIONS FOR EQUILIBRIUM OF RIGID BODIES UNDER THE ACTION OF PARALLEL AND NON-PARALLEL FORCES","question":"An object is acted upon by a system of parallel forces causing the object to be in elastic equilibrium. which of the following statement is not correct ?","images":[],"options":{"A":"The resultant of the reactant of the parallel forces is zero.","B":"The algebraic sum of all the moments of the force zero","C":"All the parallel forces must be equal in magnitude and direction","D":"sum of the forces in one direction must equal to the sum of the forces in the opposite direction"},"answer":"C","explanation":"For a body to be in static equilibrium when being acted by different forces, the forces must be equal in magnitude and direction.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2002>12","subject":"Physics","year":"2002","type":"Objective","topic":"EQUILIBRIUM OF FORCES : CONDITIONS FOR EQUILIBRIUM OF RIGID BODIES UNDER THE ACTION OF PARALLEL AND NON-PARALLEL FORCES","question":"An object ,A, is held in equilibrium as illustrated in the diagram, determine the magnitude ,W, of the weight of A","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"23N","B":"17N","C":"7N","D":"5N"},"answer":"B","explanation":"If the object is in equilibrium,  W = resultant of T1 and T2  W2 = T12 + T22  \u21d2 82 + 152  W2 = 64 + 255  W2 = 289  squaring both sides  W = 17N","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2002>13","subject":"Physics","year":"2002","type":"Objective","topic":"HOOKE\u2019S LAW, YOUNG\u2019S MODULES AND WORK DONE IN SPRINGS AND STRING :","question":"A spiral spring of natural length 30.cm and forces constant of 20Nm-1 is compressed to 20.0cm. calculate the energy stored in the spring","images":[],"options":{"A":"0.1 J","B":"1.0J","C":"10.0J","D":"100.J"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Energystored(E)=12KC2  C = 30 - 20 = 10cm = 0.1m  E=12x20x(0.1)2 = 0.1J","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2002>14","subject":"Physics","year":"2002","type":"Objective","topic":"EQUILIBRIUM OF FORCES : CONDITIONS FOR EQUILIBRIUM OF RIGID BODIES UNDER THE ACTION OF PARALLEL AND NON-PARALLEL FORCES","question":"In the diagram above, AB represents a uniform rod of length 1.50m which is in equilibrium on a pivot at P, If AP = 40cm, calculate the mass of the rod. [g = 10ms-2]","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"0.280kg","B":"0.400kg","C":"0.613kg","D":"0.800kg"},"answer":"D","explanation":"applying law of moments    Therefore,  7N x 40cm = 35cm x W  W=7N x 40cm35cm=0.8kg","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2002>15","subject":"Physics","year":"2002","type":"Objective","topic":"WORK, ENERGY AND POWER : CONCEPT OF WORK","question":"Which of the following statement correctly defines quantitatively, the work done by a force ?The product of the force and the distance moved","images":[],"options":{"A":"parallel to the line of action of the force and the reference point","B":"perpendicular to the line of action of the force from the reference point","C":"on the line through the reference point","D":"by the object"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The work done by a force is defined as the product of the force and the distance moved parallel to the line of action of the force and the reference point .","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2002>16","subject":"Physics","year":"2002","type":"Objective","topic":"WORK, ENERGY AND POWER : CONCEPT OF POWER","question":"A load of mass120kg is raised vertically through a height of 2m in 30s by a machine whose efficiency is 100%. calculate the power generated by the machine [g = 10ms-2]","images":[],"options":{"A":"60W","B":"80W","C":"100W","D":"120W"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Power=work donetime taken  since efficiency is 100%  Therefore,P=mght  P=120 \u00d7 10\u00d7230=80w","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2002>17","subject":"Physics","year":"2002","type":"Objective","topic":"MACHINES :","question":"A block and tackle system has 6 pulley . if the efficiency of the machine is 60%. determine the mechanical advantage","images":[],"options":{"A":"12.0","B":"10.0","C":"3.6","D":"1.8"},"answer":"C","explanation":"V.R = 6, Efficiency (E) = 60%  E=M.AV.R  M.A = E x V.R  M.A = 6.6 x 6  M.A = 3.6","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2002>18","subject":"Physics","year":"2002","type":"Objective","topic":"MACHINES :","question":"Which of the following actions will improve the efficiency of a pulley system?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Reducing the mass the pulley","B":"increasing the frictional force between the string of the pulley","C":"increasing the mass per unit length of the string of the pulley","D":"increasing the mass of pulley"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The efficiency of a pulley system can be improved by reducing the mass of the pulley. This is because a lighter pulley requires less force to move, which reduces the amount of energy lost to overcoming inertia and friction. Therefore, the correct answer is option 1.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2002>19","subject":"Physics","year":"2002","type":"Objective","topic":"HEAT ENERGY : TEMPERATURE AND ITS MEASUREMENT","question":"The ice and steam point of a certain thermometer are -20\u2218 and 100\u2218 respectively. calculate the celsius temperature corresponding to 70\u2218 on the thermometers","images":[],"options":{"A":"84.0\u2218C","B":"75\u2218C","C":"64.0\u2218C","D":"58.0\u2218C"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Tc100=70 - (-20)120  Tc=90 \u00d7 100120=75\u00b0C","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2002>20","subject":"Physics","year":"2002","type":"Objective","topic":"HEAT ENERGY : HEAT TRANSFER","question":"The silver coating on the inside of a vacuum flask reduces heat loss by","images":[],"options":{"A":"conduction","B":"radiation","C":"condensation","D":"convection"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The silver coating on the inside of a vacuum flask reduces heat loss by radiation. This is because silver is a good reflector of infrared radiation, which is the primary form of heat transfer in a vacuum. Therefore, the correct answer is option 2.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2002>21","subject":"Physics","year":"2002","type":"Objective","topic":"HEAT ENERGY : SPECIFIC LATENT HEAT OF VAPORISATION","question":"Water of mass120g at 50\u2218C is added to 200g of water at 10\u2218C and mixture is well stirred. calculate the temperature of the mixture [Neglect heat losses to the surrounding]","images":[],"options":{"A":"60\u2218C","B":"40\u2218C","C":"25\u2218C","D":"10\u2218C"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Using,  MC\u03b8 = M1C\u03b81 + M2C\u03b82  where M = M1 + M2  \u03b8 = common temperature   Therefore,  (120 + 200)C \u00d7 \u03b8 = 120 \u00d7 C \u00d7 50 + 200 \u00d7 C \u00d7 10  320C\u03b8 = 6000C + 2000C  \u03b8=8000C320C=25\u00b0C","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2002>22","subject":"Physics","year":"2002","type":"Objective","topic":"HEAT ENERGY : SPECIFIC LATENT HEAT OF VAPORISATION","question":"Calculate the energy required to vaporise 50g of water initially at 80\u2218C. [specific heat capacity of water = 4.2Jg-1K-1] at 80]    [Specific latent heat of vaporization of steam, L = 2260 J/g]","images":[],"options":{"A":"113,000J","B":"117,200J","C":"234,400J","D":"420,000J"},"answer":"B","explanation":"E = mC\u03b8 + mL  where,  \u03b8 = temperature required to get to steam point   \u03b8 = \u03b8s - \u03b80 = 100\u00b0C - 80\u00b0C = 20\u00b0C  E = mc\u03b8 + ml  E = 50 x 4.2 x 20 + 50 x 2260  E = 4200 + 113000  E = 117,200J","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2002>23","subject":"Physics","year":"2002","type":"Objective","topic":"PRODUCTION AND PROPAGATION OF WAVES : PRODUCTION AND PROPAGATION OF MECHANICAL WAVES","question":"What type of motion does the skin of a Talking drum perform when it is struck with a drum stick?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Random","B":"rational","C":"translational","D":"vibratory"},"answer":"D","explanation":"When a drum skin is struck with a drum stick, it vibrates. These vibrations create sound waves that we hear as the drum sound. Therefore, the motion of the drum skin is vibratory.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2002>24","subject":"Physics","year":"2002","type":"Objective","topic":"TYPES OF WAVES : TRANSVERSE AND LONGITUDINAL","question":"A slinky spring fixed at one end is placed horizontally on a table. The free end is displaced parallel to the table and then released. the resulting waveform is","images":[],"options":{"A":"transverse","B":"longitudinal","C":"stationary","D":"electromagnetic"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Longitudinal waves are waves in which the displacement of the medium is in the same direction as, or the opposite direction to, the direction of propagation of the wave.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2002>25","subject":"Physics","year":"2002","type":"Objective","topic":"PRODUCTION AND PROPAGATION OF WAVES : FREQUENCY (F), WAVELENGTH(\ud835\udecc), PERIOD (T) AND VELOCITY (V)","question":"A radio wave has a wavelength is 150m. if the velocity of radio wave in free wave is 3 \u00d7 10\u2078m/s)","images":[],"options":{"A":"4.5 \u00d71010Hz","B":"50\u00d7109Hz","C":"4.5\u00d7109Hz","D":"2.0\u00d7106Hz"},"answer":"D","explanation":"V = F\u22cb  F=V\u22cb=3 x 108150=2.0x106Hz","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2002>26","subject":"Physics","year":"2002","type":"Objective","topic":"PRODUCTION AND PROPAGATION OF WAVES : WAVEFORM","question":"In the wave equation y = E0 sin(200t - \u22bcx), E0 represent the","images":[],"options":{"A":"amplitude","B":"frequency","C":"period","D":"wavelenght"},"answer":"A","explanation":"In the wave equation y = E0 sin(200t - \u22bcx), E0 represents the amplitude of the wave. The amplitude of a wave is the maximum displacement of the wave from its equilibrium position. It is the distance from the crest or the trough of the wave to the equilibrium position. In this equation, E0 is the maximum displacement of the wave, hence it represents the amplitude.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2002>27","subject":"Physics","year":"2002","type":"Objective","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : SOURCES OF LIGHT","question":"The size of the hole of a pin hole camera is increased. The resultant image formed becomes","images":[],"options":{"A":"sharper","B":"reduced in size","C":"enlarged","D":"blurred"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The size of the hole in a pinhole camera is inversely proportional to the sharpness of the image formed. This means that as the size of the hole increases, the sharpness of the image decreases and the image becomes blurred. This is because a larger hole allows more light rays to enter at different angles, which results in a less focused image.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2002>28","subject":"Physics","year":"2002","type":"Objective","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE SURFACES","question":"The refractive index of a medium relative to air is 1.8. calculate, to the nearest degree, the critical angle for the medium","images":[],"options":{"A":"68\u2218","B":"56\u2218","C":"34\u2218","D":"18\u2218"},"answer":"C","explanation":"n = 1.8  Critical angle i = 90\u00b0  sin isin c=1.8  sin90sin c=1sin c  1sin c=1.8  sinc=18  sin-1(0.5556) = 34\u00b0","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2002>29","subject":"Physics","year":"2002","type":"Objective","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : APPLICATION OF LENSES IN OPTICAL INSTRUMENTS","question":"A converging lens of focal length 15m  form a virtual image at a point 10cm from a lens. calculate the distance of the object from the lens","images":[],"options":{"A":"10.00cm","B":"6.00cm","C":"50cm","D":"1.50cm"},"answer":"B","explanation":"1F=1U-1V(virtualisnegative)  115=1U-110  1U=115+110=530  1U=115+110=530  1U=530  U=305=6cm","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2002>30","subject":"Physics","year":"2002","type":"Objective","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : APPLICATION OF LENSES IN OPTICAL INSTRUMENTS","question":"In a compound microscope, the image formed by the objective lens is at distance of 3.0cm from the eye lens. if the final image is at 25.0cm from the eye lens, calculate the focal length of the eyes lens","images":[],"options":{"A":"0.3cm","B":"2.7cm","C":"3.4cm","D":"8.3cm"},"answer":"C","explanation":"1U+1V=1F  13+1-25=1F  1F=25 - 375=2275  F=7522=3.4","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2002>31","subject":"Physics","year":"2002","type":"Objective","topic":"SOUND WAVES : SPEED OF SOUND","question":"A pulse of a sound is transmitted from a ship and the reflection from he sea bed is recorded after 0.2s. calculate the depth of the sea.[take speed of sound in sea water  = 1560ms-1]","images":[],"options":{"A":"312.0m","B":"156.0m","C":"78.0m","D":"31.2m"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The formula to calculate the depth of the sea is d = vt/2. Substituting the given values into the formula, we get the depth of the sea as 156.0m.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2002>32","subject":"Physics","year":"2002","type":"Objective","topic":"SOUND WAVES : RESONANCE","question":"When two notes of nearly equal frequency are sounded together, a periodic rise and fall in sound intensity can be heard. this phenomenon is called","images":[],"options":{"A":"beats","B":"diffraction","C":"overtones","D":"resonance"},"answer":"A","explanation":"In acoustics, a beat is an interference pattern two sounds of slightly frequencies, perceived as a periodic variation in volume.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2002>33","subject":"Physics","year":"2002","type":"Objective","topic":"SOUND WAVES : SOURCES OF SOUND","question":"Which of the following instrument is not a wind instrument","images":[],"options":{"A":"larinet","B":"saxophone","C":"trumpet","D":"xylophone"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The xylophone is not a wind instrument. It is a percussion instrument that is played by striking wooden bars with mallets.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2002>34","subject":"Physics","year":"2002","type":"Objective","topic":"SOUND WAVES : VIBRATION IN STRINGS","question":"Which of the following actions will not cause an increase in the vibrating string?","images":[],"options":{"A":"increasing the tension in the string","B":"Decreasing the mass per unit length of the string","C":"Decreasing the lenght of the tring","D":"increasing the cross sectional area of the string"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The thicker the string the lower the frequency and pitch  F=12L&radic;&nbsp;TPA  where, A = area","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2002>35","subject":"Physics","year":"2002","type":"Objective","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : PRODUCTION OF ELECTRIC CHARGES","question":"Which of the following items can be used to compare the relative magnitude of electric charges on two bodies?","images":[],"options":{"A":"ebonite rod","B":"gold leaf electroscope","C":"proff planes","D":"the electrophorus"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A gold leaf electroscope can be used to compare the relative magnitude of electric charges on two bodies. It works by indicating the presence and magnitude of a charge through the application of electrostatic induction.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2002>36","subject":"Physics","year":"2002","type":"Objective","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : CAPACITANCE, ARRANGEMENT AND APPLICATION","question":"Three capacitor each of capacitance is 18\u00b5F are connected in series, calculate the effective capacitance of the capacitors","images":[],"options":{"A":"54.00\u00b5F","B":"18.00\u00b5F","C":"6.00\u00b5F","D":"0.17\u00b5F"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Effective capacitance (series connection)  1C=1C1+1C2+1C3  1C=118+118+118  1C=318  C=183=6.00\u00b5F","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2002>37","subject":"Physics","year":"2002","type":"Objective","topic":"GRAVITATIONAL FIELD : NEWTON\u2019S LAW OF GRAVITATION","question":"Two spheres of masses 100kg and 90 kg respectively have their centers separated by a distance of 1.0 m, calculate the magnitude of the forces of attraction between them[G = 6.70 \u00d710-11Nm2kg2]","images":[],"options":{"A":"6.70 \u00d710-11N","B":"6.70 \u00d710-10N","C":"6.03 \u00d710-10N","D":"6.03 \u00d710-7N"},"answer":"D","explanation":"F=GM1M2r2  =6.70 x 10-11 x 100 x 90(1.0)2=6.7 x 10-11 x 90001 = 60300 x 10-11 = 6.03 x 106 x 10-11  \u21d2 6.03 x 10-7N","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2002>38","subject":"Physics","year":"2002","type":"Objective","topic":"GRAVITATIONAL FIELD : ACCELERATION DUE TO GRAVITY","question":"The magnitude of the gravitational attraction between the earth and a particles is 40N. if the mass of the particle is 4kg, calculate the magnitude of the gravitational field intensity of the earth on the particles","images":[],"options":{"A":"10.0Nkg-1","B":"12.6Nkg-1","C":"25.0Nkg-1","D":"160.0Nkg-1"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The gravitational field intensity of the earth on the particle is given by  FGm=40N4Kg=10NKg-1","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2002>39","subject":"Physics","year":"2002","type":"Objective","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : CURRENT ELECTRICITY","question":"Local action is normally prevented in a simple electric cell by","images":[],"options":{"A":"introducing an oxidising agent in the acid","B":"not drawing current continuously for long period","C":"amalgamating the surface of the zinc plate","D":"using a porous pot to isolate the zinc from the acid"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Local action in a simple electric cell is prevented by amalgamating the surface of the zinc plate. Local action refers to the self-discharge of a cell when small areas of the zinc plate, due to impurities, act as local cells with the rest of the plate. This results in wastage of zinc even when no current is being drawn from the cell. Amalgamation is the process of coating the zinc plate with a layer of mercury. This provides a uniform surface and prevents local action.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2002>40","subject":"Physics","year":"2002","type":"Objective","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : PRODUCTION OF ELECTRIC CURRENT","question":"The lead-acid accumulator consist of","images":[],"options":{"A":"lead as the positive electrode","B":"lead oxide as the negative electrode","C":"Hydrochloric acid as the electrolyte","D":"tetraoxosulphate(VI) acid as the electrolyte"},"answer":"D","explanation":"A lead-acid accumulator consists of sulphuric acid or tetraoxosulphate (vi) acid as the electrolyte.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2002>41","subject":"Physics","year":"2002","type":"Objective","topic":"ELECTROMAGNETIC FIELD : FARADAY\u2019S LAW","question":"Which of the following action will not lead to an increase in their induced e.m.f in a coil of wire rotating between the poles of a magnet ? increasing the","images":[],"options":{"A":"strength of the magnet","B":"number of turns in the coil","C":"speed of rotation of the coil","D":"Gap between the poles of the magnet"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The induced electromotive force (e.m.f) in a coil of wire rotating between the poles of a magnet is determined by the strength of the magnet, the number of turns in the coil, and the speed of rotation of the coil. Increasing the gap between the poles of the magnet will not increase the induced e.m.f. In fact, it will decrease the magnetic field strength and thus reduce the induced e.m.f.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2002>42","subject":"Physics","year":"2002","type":"Objective","topic":"ELECTROMAGNETIC FIELD : MOTOR-GENERATOR EFFECT","question":"A transformer has 400 turns and 200 turns in the primary and secondary winding respectively. if the the current in the primary and secondary winding are 3A and 5A respectively, calculate the efficiency of the transformer","images":[],"options":{"A":"85.0%","B":"83.3%","C":"37.5%","D":"30.0%"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Es \u03b1 Ns  Es = KNs  Ep \u03b1 Np  Ep = KNp  IE = power  Power in secondary (Ps) = IsEs = KIsNs  Power in the primary (Pp) = IpEp = KIpNp  Efficiency=PsPp\u00d7100%=kIsNsKIpNp\u00d7100%  =IsNsIpNp\u00d7100%  Efficiency=200400\u00d753\u00d7100=83.3%","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2002>43","subject":"Physics","year":"2002","type":"Objective","topic":"MAGNETIC FIELD : THE EARTH\u2019S MAGNETIC FIELD","question":"A freely-suspended magnet swinging in a horizontal plane comes to rest with its axis pointing approximately.","images":[],"options":{"A":"north-south","B":"south-west","C":"north-east","D":"south-east"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Since the magnet is swinging horizontally,","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2002>44","subject":"Physics","year":"2002","type":"Objective","topic":"ELECTROMAGNETIC FIELD : INDUCTANCE","question":"Calculate the inductance,L, of the coil in the circuit diagram shown above","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"3.8H","B":"0.6H","C":"0.4H","D":"0.2H"},"answer":"B","explanation":"XL (Reactance) = V/I = 240/2 = 120\u03a9  XL = 2\u03c0FL  making L the subject  L=XL2\u03c0F=1202\u03c0 \u00d7 100/\u03c0  =120200=0.6  L = 0.6H","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2002>45","subject":"Physics","year":"2002","type":"Objective","topic":"STRUCTURE OF THE ATOM : ENERGY QUANTIZATION","question":"In a model of the hydrogen atom, the energy level Wn are given by the formula Wn = -R/N2. Where n is an integer and R is a constant, Determine the energy  released in the transition form n = 3 to n =2","images":[],"options":{"A":"R/5","B":"-R/4","C":"5R/36","D":"-5R/36"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Wn=-Rn2  when energy levels are n = 3 and n = 2  Energy released is given by  Wn3-n2=-R(132+122)=-R(19-14)  =-R(4-936)=-R(-536)=5R36","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2002>46","subject":"Physics","year":"2002","type":"Objective","topic":"STRUCTURE OF THE NUCLEUS : RADIOACTIVITY","question":"If a radioactive atom emits a beta particle, its mass number","images":[],"options":{"A":"increase by one","B":"remains the same","C":"decreases by one","D":"increase by two"},"answer":"B","explanation":"When a radioactive atom emits a beta particle, a neutron in the nucleus is converted into a proton and an electron (the beta particle). This increases the atomic number by one, but the mass number (the total number of protons and neutrons) remains the same, as a neutron has been converted into a proton. Therefore, the correct answer is option 2.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2002>47","subject":"Physics","year":"2002","type":"Objective","topic":"STRUCTURE OF THE ATOM : PHOTOELECTRIC EFFECT","question":"When light fall on a metallic surface, the number of electrons that can be emitted would depend solely on the","images":[],"options":{"A":"area of the metallic surface","B":"frequency of the light","C":"intensity of the light","D":"time of exposure of etallic to light"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The number of electrons that can be emitted when light falls on a metallic surface depends on the frequency of the light. This is based on the photoelectric effect, which states that electrons are emitted from the surface of a metal when light of a certain frequency (or higher) shines on it. The frequency of the light determines the energy of the photons, and if this energy is high enough, it can overcome the work function of the metal and cause electrons to be emitted.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2002>48","subject":"Physics","year":"2002","type":"Objective","topic":"STRUCTURE OF THE NUCLEUS : FUSION AND FISSION","question":"Which of the following material is used to control the rate of neutron production in a nuclear reactor?","images":[],"options":{"A":"boron rods","B":"concrete shield","C":"graphite rods","D":"uranium rods"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Boron rods are used to control the rate of neutron production in a nuclear reactor. Boron has a high cross-section for absorption of neutrons, which means it is very effective at capturing and thus reducing the number of free neutrons in the reactor. This helps to control the rate of the nuclear chain reaction.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2002>49","subject":"Physics","year":"2002","type":"Objective","topic":"STRUCTURE OF THE NUCLEUS : FUSION AND FISSION","question":"Which of the following is usually used to cause fission in an atomic reactor?","images":[],"options":{"A":"alpha particles","B":"beta particles","C":"electrons neutrons","D":"neutrons"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Neutrons are usually used to cause fission in an atomic reactor. Fission is the process by which the nucleus of an atom splits into two or more smaller nuclei, along with the release of a large amount of energy. This process is initiated by the absorption of a neutron by the nucleus of the atom.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2002>50","subject":"Physics","year":"2002","type":"Objective","topic":"STRUCTURE OF THE NUCLEUS : COMPOSITION OF THE NUCLEUS","question":"A nuclide X is produced by bombarding a nitrogen (N) nucleus with an alpha (\u03b1) particles wit release of heavy hydrogen (D) nucleus as shown by following nuclear equation. \u03b1 + 147\u2192pqX + 21D. Determine the values of p and q in the equation.","images":[],"options":{"A":"12 and 6","B":"14 and 7","C":"16 and 8","D":"19 and 8"},"answer":"C","explanation":"\u03b1 + 148N \u2192 pqX + 21D  42He + 147N \u2192 pqX + 21D  Hence,  4 + 14 = p + 2  p = 18 - 2 = 16  then,  2 + 7 = q + 1  9 = q + 1  q = 9 - 1 = 8    P = 16 and q = 8","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"}];